yle="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Partner, Deighton Pierce Glynn Solicitors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">11)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Hamish Arnott, Partner, Bhatt Murphy Solicitors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">12)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Jed Pennington, solicitor, Bhatt Murphy Solicitors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">13)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Camilla Graham-Wood, solicitor, Birnberg Peirce and Partners Solicitors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">14)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Khuluza Mlotshwa, ex-detainee and law stude</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">15)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Aisha Kabejja, ex-detainee and student</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The group’s terms of reference are as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The Mental Health and Immigration Detention Action Group (MHIDAG) is a voluntary and unfunded group with a membership of lawyers, health professionals, ex-detainees and NGO workers. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The MHIDAG:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt 0pt 26.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">is seriously concerned about the mental health of those held </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">under Immigration Powers;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt 0pt 26.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">considers that aspects of the current detention and healthcare policy and their current implementation are detrimental to the mental health of immigration detainees; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt 0pt 26.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">and will be marshalling evidence and submissions to influenc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e a change for the better for both individual detainees and detainees as a whole.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The MHIDAG will do its work through collaborative discussion and information exchange and through influencing external bodies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG is grateful for the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prov</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ide </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">written </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to the Joint Committee on Human Rights’ enquiry into the impact of the proposed legal aid reforms on access to justice</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, announced on 18 July 2013</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG has serious concerns about the proposals, which are made all the more acute by th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Government’s decision to introduce them by way of secondary legislation, thereby curtailing the opportunity for Parliamentary scrutiny of measures which will, in themselves, curtail the opportunity for judicial scrutiny of executive action. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the proposals contained in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> must now be seen in the context of the latest proposals to reform judicial review contained in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposals for Reform, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which, if implemented, will have the effect of reducing access to judici</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al review for both individuals and representative groups, such as NGOs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, charities and campaigning organisations</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Members of MHIDAG are available to provide oral evidence to the Committee, if such evidence would be of value. In particular, we would urge th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e Committee to hear evidence from people who have been in immigration detention and can give evidence about how legal aid ensured that they were able to access justice. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Summary</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">profound</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concerns about the proposed residence test and the propos</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ed cuts to funding for judicial review.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> In MHIDAG’s view these proposals have serious implications for access to justice and for the protection of human rights. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> effect of the residence test will be that people who have been unlawfully detained in immigration detention or suffered ill-treatment in immigration detention, but who have been released, will be unable to bring claims for false imprisonment, assault</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> mis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">feasance in public office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and significant breaches of the European Convention on Human Rights (ECHR)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:14.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 11.67pt; padding-left:6.33pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Thus w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hile at first sight it may appear that immigration detainees have been exempted from the residence test, this is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potentially </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">misleading. Ex-detai</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nees will be prevented from bringing civil claims against the detaining authorities, including claims for damages.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Such claims are of constitutional significance in enforcing individual rights against detaining authorities.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:8pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:8pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The proposed residence test wi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ll have a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> particular</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ly</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">adverse </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effect on ex-detainees who suffer from mental health problems.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This group of ex-detainees will face particular obstacles in bringing challenges against the detaining authorities, and their specific need for community care and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> support is likely to go unmet if they cannot seek legal advice and assistance to enforce the duties owed to them. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG is of the view that exceptional funding is not an answer to this: the exceptional fundin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g scheme is new and un-tested. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">experience of members of MHIDAG and e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">vidence from organisations such as the Public Law Project demonstrate the systemic failings that beset</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the exceptional funding scheme such that it cannot be relied upon to ensure that the residence test is compliant wit</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h the ECHR and non-discriminatory. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG urges the Committee to consider the proposals to cut funding for judicial review in the context of the further proposals to reform judicial review, set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Judicial Review: Proposals for Further Reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on 6 Se</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ptember 2013. Taken as a whole, these proposals will restrict access to judicial review for impecunious claimants with meritorious cases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, with a particular adverse effect on immigration detainees with mental health problems</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The new proposals do not allevi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ate the access to justice concerns raised by the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proposals. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Detailed submissions</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> proposed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline"> residence test</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG welcomes the Lord Chancellor’s concession that immigration detainees seeking to challenge their detention should be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">exempt from the residence test. However, this concession does not meet MHIDAG’s profound concerns about the proposed residence test. First and foremost, MHIDAG is absolutely opposed to a residence test for legal aid on the grounds that it is discriminatory</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, abrogates the common law right of access to the courts and undermines the fundamental principle of the rule of law that all are equal before the law. While the exception for immigration detainees challenging their detention is welcome, it does not cure t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he proposed residence test of its unjustifiable discrimination </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its violation of fundamental constitutional rights. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secondly, MHIDAG is of the view that such a draconian proposal should have the benefit of full Parliamentary scrutiny. The residence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> test will create a class of individuals who are unable to access the courts so as to enforce the rights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">conferred upon them by primary legislation. The decision to introduce such a measure by secondary legislation has the effect of ousting fundamental rig</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hts, and judicial review, by the backdoor. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, the exception for immigration detainees challenging their detention is an exception of form, not substance: it does not offer adequate protection for immigration detainees’ rights and nor does it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provide safeguards against abuse by public authorities. The Government’s response to the consultation Annex B states at paragraph 25 that only the following detention cases will be exempt from the residence test:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 39.35pt 10pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">“125. Having carefully considered consultat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ion responses, we have concluded that there are further limited circumstances where applicants for civil legal aid on certain matters of law (as set out in Schedule 1 to LASPO) would not be required to meet the residence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">test. The test will not apply to th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">e following categories of case (which broadly relate to an individual’s liberty, or where the individual is particularly vulnerable or where the case relates to the protection of children): </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 39.35pt 10pt 42.55pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">Detention cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">(paragraphs 5, 20, 25, 26 and 27 (and challenges </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">to the lawfulness of detention by way of judicial review under paragraph 19) of Part 1 of Schedule 1 to LASPO)” </span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It follows that cases a person</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is no longer detained but seeks to challenge the lawfulness of a period of detention in the past</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, or their t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">reatment in detention in the past</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, and to claim damages, will be subject to the residence test. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This will include cases of assault, misfeasance in public office</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">false imprisonment and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">breaches of the ECHR (A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rticles 3, 4, 5 and 8) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will result in insufficie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nt procedural safeguards to ensure that the right to compensation for unlawful detention under Article </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5(5) ECHR is protected. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This is of serious concern because it creates a lacuna in the protections individuals are afforded when they have been subject </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unlawful </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or abuses of power in detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> The most obvious recent example arises from the cases of women in Yarl’s Wood Immigration Removal Centre who have alleged that they were the subject of inappropriate sexual contact with IRC staff.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> These cases raise serious issues about the abuse of public office and t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he protection of the vulnerable but could not be brought</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> under the proposed residence test because the individuals would not have access to legal aid. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Similar concerns arise in the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ontext of the detention of the mentally ill. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Findings consistently report high levels of mental illness among immigration detainees. High proportions of immigration detainees display clinically significant levels of depression, post-traumatic stress disord</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">er (PTSD), anxiety, intense fear, sleep disturbance, profound hopelessness, self-harm and suicidal ideation. In a study monitoring immigration detainees over a nine month period, 85 per cent reported chronic depressive symptoms, 65 per cent reported suicid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al ideation, 39 per cent experienced paranoid delusions, 21 per cent showed signs of psychosis and 57 per cent required psychotropic medication.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Mental health care in immigration detention is often woefully inadequate. Reports from independent monitorin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g bodies such as the HM Inspectorate of Prisons (HMIP), have consistently and routinely found profound failures in the care of the mentally ill detainees in immigration removal centres. By way of example only, in 2009 HMIP described its report on Tinsley H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ouse IRC as “deeply depressing”. It found that there was no regular input from community mental health teams and there was a lack of active nursing input for detainees with severe mental health needs, giving the following example:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“We found a lack of nursi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng input into the care of one detainee who had become agitated and distressed. Although she was subsequently seen and treated by a psychiatrist, a nurse who had been on duty since 7am told us at 2:15pm that he had not yet seen the detainee that day. There </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was also no documented care plan for this detainee, which was unacceptable practice.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2010 HMIP described Brook House IRC as follows:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“[W]e were disturbed to find one of the least safe immigration detention facilities we have inspected, with deeply </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">frustrated detainees and demoralised staff, some of whom lacked the necessary confidence to manage those in their care. At the time of the inspection, Brook House was an unsafe place.”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In 2011 the HMIP inspection of Harmondsworth IRC identified the follow</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing concerns, among many others:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“A major area for on-going concern was health care, which remained a source of considerable complaint from detainees. Mental health needs were under identified and the inpatients department was described by staff themselves</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as a ‘forgotten world’. The poor service we witnessed the last time we visited was still evident in many respects […]”</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the last two years the High Court has found four breaches of the absolute prohibition of inhuman and degrading treatment in Article </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3 of the European Convention on Human Rights arising out of the treatment of mentally ill detainees in immigration detention: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (S) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">[2011] EWHC 2120;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (BA) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">[2011] EW</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">HC 2748;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">D) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">[2012] EWHC 2501; and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">R (HA (Nigeria)) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> [2012] EWHC 979. This is unprecedented. The cases that gave rise to these most serious of human rights violation</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s were all brought before the High Court by way of judicial review.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he effect of the proposed residence test will be to remove </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from public funding those cases where a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ny</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> person was unlawfully detained or mistreated in detention, but who is no longer in detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, thereby removing the remedy of civil claims to establish state accountability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">will</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> allow the most intrusive executive action against the most vulnerable in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dividuals to go unscrutinised, and to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">deprive those individuals </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> an effective remedy. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It is the experience of lawyers specialising in this field that the majority of cases challenging the legality of immigration detention by way of civil actions are su</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ccessful and the costs of the claim are recovered from the Defendant. MHIDAG is concerned that public authorities like the Home Office have a vested </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">interest in these cases not being brought before the courts. This refle</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cts an underlying concern that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fundi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng of contentious litigation should have been brought back  under direct political control of the Government when the LSC, an independent agency, was disbanded.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, MHIDAG is concerned about the implications for access to justice that the proposed residence test will have on mentally ill immigrants who are released from detention and need care and support in the community. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">As stated above, immigration det</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ainees suffer from high levels of mental illness. It is our experience that detainees’ mental illness is liable to deteriorate in detention. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Home Office policy states that immigration detainees who suffer from serious mental health problems that cannot be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">satisfactorily managed in detention should only be detained in exceptional circumstances. It follows that immigration detainees that are suffering from serious mental illness may be released into the community, where it is vital that they receive the care </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and support that they need. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The residence test will prevent ex-detainees from having legal advice and assistance to seek the community care and support that they need. For those ex-detainees that suffer from mental illness, this may create an insurmounta</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ble barrier to them accessing justice.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG is aware that the Government proposes to amend Schedule 1 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012 so as to make exceptional funding available to people who do not meet the requirements of the residence test, or who cannot p</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rove that they meet the requirements of the residence test. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">However, MHIDAG is of the strong view that exceptional funding is not an answer to the iniquities of the residence test, and that the exceptional funding regime is incapable of rendering the resid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ence test compliant with the ECHR. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are a number of systemic flaws in the exceptional funding scheme which make it inaccessible for applicants. For example:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Exceptional funding applications are made at risk. In our experience, they involve a substan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tial amount of work that is in addition to the work needed on the underlying case. The absence of payment for making exceptional funding applications creates a chilling effect, evidenced most clearly by the low numbers of applications made to the Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Agency since 1 April 2013.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The test for getting exceptional funding is a complex legal one that it is difficult for applicants to understand and address without the assistance of a lawyer. The applicants who are the most vulnerable, and therefore the most</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in need of exceptional funding, will be the least able to navigate the exceptional funding scheme. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no emergency procedure for accessing exceptional funding. For ex-detainees in need of urgent community care, for example, the exceptional funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">scheme will be impossible to access in order to safeguard their needs, creating an unacceptable risk that their human rights will be breached either by the delay, or by the fact of having to represent themselves in the proceedings. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is no procedure f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or exempting children or people who lack capacity from the exceptional funding regime. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In the absence of a litigation friend or pro bono legal representation, t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">his means that the most vulnerable applicants</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> who are unable to conduct proceedings alone, face </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a complete bar from accessing the courts.  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic; text-decoration:underline">The proposed cuts to funding for judicial review</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Any analysis of the proposals to cut funding for judicial review in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Transforming Legal Aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> must now been seen in the context of the further proposals set out in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Ju</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">dicial Review: Proposals for Reform</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, published on 6 September 2013. Taken as a whole, these proposals will limit access to judicial review for individuals and representative groups. The effect will be to shield executive action from scrutiny and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">prevent me</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ritorious cases </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">from being heard by the courts.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG reminds the Committee that the proposal to cut funding for pre-permission judicial reviews is aimed at meritorious claims brought on behalf of individuals who do not have the means to pay for a lawyer and who have no other available remedy for resol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ving their legal problem. This is because legal aid will not currently be provided for a judicial review claim that does not meet these criterion. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">For mentally ill detainees, judicial review is routinely the only route of redress for the human rights </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">abuses that they suffer. Judicial review is also the only and appropriate way that unlawful policies or unlawful application of policies can be challenged and remedied. For example, judicial review litigation recently exposed “disturbing” evidence of syste</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mic failures concerning the detention of victims of torture.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In addition, a string of four judicial reviews in the High Court identified that mentally ill immigration detainees had suffered serious breaches of their human rights while in detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ne reason for this view is that strong claims routinely settle prior to permission. Our experience is that public bodies sometimes make their offer of settlement conditional upon the claimant’s solicitors not pursuing a costs order. If this proposal is bro</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ught into force, such offers of settlement, which are usually in the best interests of the client, will prevent the solicitor from being paid at all. This will pit solicitors against their clients, creating an ethical dilemma that is impossible to resolve,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and it will mean that public bodies are able to act unlawfully with impunity. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secondly, unlike any other area of civil litigation, the nature of judicial review proceedings makes it difficult to assess the merits at the outset of a case. The</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> reasons for</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> this</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The test for granting permission is not a fixed one, meaning that claimant lawyers do not know from the outset what hurdle(s) they will have to jump for permission to be granted. Lord Bingham explained the need for flexibility in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Sharma v. Deputy D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">irector of Public Prosecutions &amp; Ors (Trinidad and Tobago)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> [2006] UKPC 57 at paragraph 14, as follows:</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 34pt 0pt 53.85pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">“The ordinary rule now is that the court will refuse leave to claim judicial review unless satisfied that there is an arguable ground for judicial review</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> having a realistic prospect of success and not subject to a discretionary bar such as delay or an alternative remedy: R v Legal Aid Board, Ex p Hughes (1992) 5 Admin LR 623, 628; Fordham, Judicial Review Handbook, 4th ed (2004), p 426. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">But arguability can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">not be judged without reference to the nature and gravity of the issue to be argued. It is a test which is flexible in its application</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">” (emphasis added).</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is a wide disparity in the number of permission grants made by different judges. This proposal w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould make payment conditional on a judicial lottery that is impossible to predict.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The claimant will routinely not be in possession of the relevant information for a proper merits assessment of the claim to take place until after the claim has been issued </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or even until after permission has been granted and full disclosure has been made by the Defendant. Our experience is that disclosure from the defendant public body is routinely delayed until the Acknowledgement of Service or until the defendant serves its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> evidence after permission is granted. This reality is reflected in the Legal Aid Agency’s standard limitations on funding certificates, which requires the merits of a claim to be addressed by the claimant’s lawyers in a further application to the Agency f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ollowing the refusal of permission on the papers or, if permission is granted, following service of the defendant’s evidence.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The time limits for bringing a judicial review are not fixed: the promptness requirement means that claimant providers may be of t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he firmly and honestly held view that a claim has been brought promptly, but the permission judge takes a different view. A claim may be knocked back because of timing, regardless of the merits of the substantive issues.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.3pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Events that are beyond the control </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">of the claimant or his/her representatives may render the issue in dispute academic (for example, a policy change, or the actions of a third party), after the claim has been issued but before the permission stage. This has nothing to do with the merits of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the case but will have the effect of preventing the claim from proceeding to or past permission. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Furthermore, MHIDAG emphasises that the incentive to bring strong claims already exists. First, legal aid will not be granted for weak cases. This exposes th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e fallacy of the suggestion that this proposal is designed to weed out unmeritorious claims. Second, legal aid rates have fallen in real terms since </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">1994. The only way that legal aid public lawyers can make their practice viable is by getting costs orders </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">inter partes</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> rates. That means winning cases. A lawyer that does not win cases, will not be able to make their practice financially viable. There is therefore already a strong disincentive to bring unmeritorious claims. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">MHIDAG does not consider that the proposal to give the Legal Aid Agency a discretion to pay providers for judicial reviews that do not reach the permission stage </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meets these concerns. First, it does not address the situation where a strong case settles bef</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore it is issued. In such circumstances the LAA will not be able to exercise their discretion to pay the claimant lawyers. Second, it does not address the situation where a claim is refused permission, even though it was not wrongly or poorly brought. The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">amended proposal will therefore have the same chilling effect on judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and will mean that individuals will be prevented from challenging the actions of the state. For immigration detainees, particularly those with mental health problems, this </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">represents a serious incursion into their right to access the courts, which will in turn undermine their ability to protect their human rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">7 September 2013</span></p><div style="width:auto; height:auto; float:right;"><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">9</span></p></div><p style="margin:0pt 18pt 0pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> These areas of law remain in scope for civil legal aid under Part 1, Schedule 1 of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act 2012. However, the exemptions for the residence test only apply to paragra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">phs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> 5, 20, 25, 26 and 27. This therefore excludes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">paragraphs 6 (community care), 21 (abuse of position or powers by a public authority), 22 (breach of Convention r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">ights by a public authority) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">and 43 (claims</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> under the Equality Act 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">). </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> The allegations have been widely reported. See for example: </span><a href="http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/sep/21/sexual-abuse-yarls-wood-immigration"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.theguardian.com/uk-news/2013/sep/21/sexual-abuse-yarls-wood-immigration</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> “Mental he</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">alth implications of detaining asylum seekers: systematic review”, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">British Journal of Psychiatry </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">2009, Katy Robjant, Rita Hassan and Cornelius Katona, p.307.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> They reflect a significant number of other judicial review cases challenging the lawfulness of i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">mmigration detention and its compatibility with Article 3 ECHR, which have been resolved through settlement without the necessity for a court hearing. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (EO, RA, CE, OE and RAN) v Secretary of State for the Home Department </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[2013] EWHC 1236 (Admin).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">(HA (Nigeria)) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt"> [2012] EWHC 979; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (BA) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[2011] EWHC 2748; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (S) v Secretary of State for the Home Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[2011] EWHC 2120; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">R (D) v Secretary of State for the Home </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Department</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt">[2012] EWHC 2501.</span></p></body></html>